# EVA — defining the MVP and product scope

## What I did

Refined EVA from a high-level concept into a clear product definition.

Defined the core MVP:
- voice-based interaction as the main input
- simple interface with a single main action (press and speak)
- core functionalities: reminders, basic calendar queries and voice responses

Clarified what is NOT part of the MVP (proactivity, messaging, complex integrations, etc.).

Also structured the product around a clear target user (elderly people with low digital confidence) and defined principles for usability and trust.

## What I learned

The hard part is not adding features, but deciding what to remove.

For this type of product, simplicity is not a nice-to-have — it is the product itself.

Voice interaction changes everything:
latency, clarity and trust matter more than functionality.

Designing for elderly users forces much better product decisions:
less abstraction, more clarity, stronger constraints.

## Next

- Validate the concept with real users before building further
- Test whether the voice interaction feels natural in practice
- Build the minimal version of the voice loop (input → AI → response)
